<p><b>A/HRC/16/43/Add.4 
</b></p>
<p><b>2</b> GE.11-10218 
</p>
<p>armed highway robbers (<i>coupeurs de route</i>) terrorize the civilian population and prevent 
them returning home. The Central African security forces do not have the capacity to 
protect the population adequately. A reduction in MINURCAT&#8217;s small military force and a 
rapid demobilization of armed groups might increase the existing insecurity. The 
Representative recommends that the Government should cooperate with the international 
community and the governments of neighbouring countries to improve the protection of the 
civilian population. 
</p>
<p> While welcoming the slight reduction in the number of serious human rights 
violations by the State security forces, the Representative is concerned at allegations of new 
cases of violations by the State, particularly in Bamingui-Bangoran prefecture. Some armed 
groups also commit serious violations of international humanitarian law, carry out 
summary executions and attacks on civilian populations, and recruit children to their ranks. 
</p>
<p> The Representative notes with concern that politicians and military officers 
suspected of serious violations continue to enjoy complete impunity. 
 The Representative welcomes the fact that the Government has begun to take 
measures to draw up a legal and political framework to protect internally displaced persons. 
He recommends that the Government should draft and adopt a law and a political strategy 
on displacement, based on the recommendations of the national workshop held on 15 and 
16 July 2010 in Bangui, to which he contributed. 
 </p>

<p><b>A/HRC/16/43/Add.4 
</b></p>
